<br>
My honest advice:  Duo with a shaman, seriously. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=balanzsonofanz>Balanz son of Anz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Abuser of EZCodes</span><br>  Posts: 2960<br> <font color=#333333>(2/20/03 7:00:31 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=990.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: The Pet Solution?</span><hr size=1> Whereas I disagree with <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Rthen</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, I have long awaited concrete proposals from him, since he has thought long and hard about the weaknesses of the mage class.<br>
<br>
There are several threads discussing how to remedy <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>PoP</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> mage soloability.  Assuming that mage pets need fixing, the vast majority of proposed solutions all involve effectively increasing elemental toughness, e.g.:<br>
<br>
Increasing pet hitpoints.<br>
Adding a slow proc, either innate, or through a summoned weapon.<br>
A <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;stun shield,&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> like a damage shield that stuns the attacker, either innate, or through a buff.<br>
<br>
Since slow is indisputably a profound ability, and the most obvious solution to tanking <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>PoP</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> mobs, it is not surprising it is often proposed.<br>
<br>
However, the root of the problem is actually not with the mage or their elemental <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>per se</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, but rather the new environment that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>PoP</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> presents us.<br>
<br>
When modelling fights, I often come across the factor:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Power = Hit Points * Damage Per Second</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
In <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>PoP</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, we shifted to mobs whose power is mostly in DPS.  This works against tanks, including our pets, and benefits damage dealers.<br>
<br>
An alternate solution is to have <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>(or perhaps discover)</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> mobs whose balance of power more shifted towards hitpoints and less DPS.  Then pets could be chained or sustained as mages traditional do.  It would also make groups not so much held hostage by the presence or absence of a slower.<br>
<br>
I think <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Rthen</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->'s emotional reaction here is an honest one: dismay at seeing a beastlord solo by having his pet tank when mages are forced to give up their cherished tactics.<br>
<br>
Properly this belongs in class balance, but there is no harm leaving it here.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Razamatazz Pizzazz</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
